<font color="#FF0000">THE SPIRIT OF OUR WEAPONS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 23 12:10:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Silent Warrior and Humming Eagle;<br>
&quot;Do you believe a warriors spirit is in his weapons?&quot;<br>
Some Marines used to name their 60's, Dennis Dustin and Daryl Borgman in 3rd platoon (one day I'll tell you about them, still trying to find them). They named their 60 &quot;Widow Maker.&quot; <br><br>
Do weapons have a spirit; is it their owners spirit or are the weapons of war especially protected by divine grace? Who knows, I mention two special guns both m-60's in the book, both of them from my squad. One I cannot mention, not now, it is in the book. In San Antonio, I mentioned that 60 to the women who was interested in publishing the book; she had goose bumps running up and down her arms, then broke down and cried. <br><br>
There was another 60, the one I used in Nam, could not name it. It was special, burned three of its barrels but kept the gun. Ate on it, used it as a pillow, snipped with it, killed with it, sat on it, cleaned it, slept with it, loved it, and it rewarded me. At times, it seemed like it responded with its own self-will and determination to survive. At times it did, sometimes it became me and I became the gun and sometimes we were the same. <br>
Often it opened up on its own, many times before I even hit the ground. It talked; it laughed, sang, danced and loved to announce to the world that it had entered the game. <br>
Some Marines in my squad honored it, carried its ammo without complaint, the lieutenant knew that once he heard it singing we were all going to be all right. <br>
Other Marines when they heard its sound found courage, pride and honor and advanced against the hail of bullets knowing that that crazy gun shooting from the hip was keeping the gooks heads down and everything was going to be alright. <br>
It was shot during operation Foster, but it did not die. Gook sniper shot out its trigger-housing pin while I was firing. Called the corpsmen up and everything. Took white tape from the corpsmen and wrapped up its wound and it kept firing long enough for us to get out of the kill zone.  <br><br>
One day our platoon had been pinned down, I had not been able to opened up because there was no place to set up the gun. I finally crawled out to the open, where the NVA would not expect fire to come from; it was our only chance. The platoon had already sustained 12 Wia's, 1 Kia. <br><br>
FROM Dreams of Glory, Clear Fields of Fire, Copyright 1967 Cook Barela<br><br>
&quot;Chief looked my way, and realized that I was about to open up, he reached up and snapped off the twenty round magazine he carried upside down on his helmet. The heavy-duty inch wide rubber band that held it tight against his helmet snapped back in place. He quick released and changed the magazine in his M14. <br>
Va-Da-Da-Da-Da-VVRRRRRRRRDa-Da-Da-UMMMMMMMMMMM, I opened full throttle at the base of the trees and sprayed the area with a steady flow of controlled automatic machine gun fire. <br>
The guns explosive sound roared across the landscape and added a new sound to the chaos of war. The roaring sound vibrated across the open rice paddy fields. It seemed as if the sounds the gun made went all the way out to the base of the An Hoa Mountains bounced back and boldly announced the guns entrance into the battlefield. <br>
Red-hot tracers were pouring out with intense determination from the gun. The battle had waged on for about twenty minutes and the guns roar wanted to be heard above the clamor. <br>
Over to my left a Marine opened fire from behind the embankment cried out, Yeahhhh!!!&quot; Others joined in, &quot;All right!!!&quot; and the platoon unleashed a fierily violent and explosive discharge of penned up frustration and explosive fire power that had been silent in their weapons. All clicked on to full automatic and in the next few moments we unloaded a destructive force of fire power that reeked with vengeance. Grenades were thrown and the blooper fired off grenades in rapid succession. Chief to my right arose on one knee and opened up with his M14, in full automatic. He unloaded the magazine full of red tracers at the base of the tree line. At about the same time another cluster of red tracers were being fired from my left side and I thought that it was Dustin or Borgman from 3rd platoon opening up with another M60, but it was Perry. He and Chief had both unleashed a magazine full of red tracers at the enemy. The ricocheting red hot tracers mixed in with every fifth red tracer I was firing from the gun and they perforated the air with a fierily glow that looked awesome. It looked like and sounded as if the fourth of July had exploded on the ground.&quot;<br><br>

